<h2>Common Mistakes Homeowners Make When Hiring a Contractor</h2>
<p>Hiring the wrong contractor can turn your dream project into a nightmare. Here are the most common pitfalls to avoid in your search.</p>

<h2>Choosing the Absolute Cheapest Bid</h2>
<p>An unusually low bid is a major red flag. It often indicates an inexperienced contractor, subpar materials, uninsured labor, or an incomplete understanding of the project scope. This initial savings almost always leads to expensive change orders or costly repairs down the line.</p>

<h2>Not Getting a Detailed, Written Contract</h2>
<p>A handshake is not a contract. Your agreement should be in writing and detail the full scope of work, a payment schedule, material allowances, a projected timeline, and how change orders will be handled. This document protects both you and the contractor.</p>

<h2>Failing to Verify License and Insurance</h2>
<p>Always verify that your contractor holds a current City of Chicago General Contractor license (or the equivalent in your suburb) and carries both general liability and worker's compensation insurance. Ask for the certificates. This is non-negotiable for your financial protection.</p>

